{"summary":"All four amendments identify real defects or missing coverage in the timeout and process-management changes: timeout cleanup is bypassed by the service wrapper, timeout artifact preservation is not tested, non-Unix timeout handling can leak child processes, and exit code 127 is being misclassified as a missing backend binary after successful spawn.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-3-a95af876","decision":"accept","rationale":"`src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs` starts an outer `tokio::time::timeout(request.timeout, ...)` around `adapter.invoke()`, while `src/adapters/process_backend.rs` starts another timeout with the same duration later inside `spawn_and_wait()`. Because the outer timer starts first, the inner timeout path that calls `preserve_failed_artifacts()` is effectively preempted in normal service use. The service timeout only calls `cancel()`, which does not preserve Codex temp artifacts, so timeout diagnostics can be lost."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-e384feeb","decision":"accept","rationale":"The existing timeout test in `tests/unit/process_backend_test.rs` only checks that the error is classified as `FailureClass::Timeout`. It does not verify the observable cleanup side effect under `runtime/failed`, so a regression in artifact preservation would pass unnoticed. The exact assertions may need to vary by backend, but the coverage gap described by the amendment is real and worth fixing."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-1c23f8ce","decision":"accept","rationale":"On non-Unix, `send_sigkill()` and `send_sigterm()` return `Unsupported` when the process still exists. `spawn_background_reap()` ignores the `send_sigkill()` failure and then awaits `child.wait()` forever, which keeps ownership of `ManagedChild` alive and prevents `kill_on_drop(true)` from helping. In the service timeout path, `cancel()` can also fail early on non-Unix and that error is ignored by the caller. The result is a genuine timeout-with-live-child leak on Windows."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-ccb079f3","decision":"accept","rationale":"Actual missing executables are already detected before or at spawn time through `resolve_binary()` and `command.spawn()` returning `ErrorKind::NotFound`. After a child has successfully spawned, exit status `127` is not reliable evidence that the backend binary itself was missing; it is just process-defined exit behavior, especially for wrapper scripts or CLIs that invoke subcommands. Classifying every post-spawn `127` as `BinaryNotFound` incorrectly turns a retryable process failure into a non-retryable configuration error."}]}